@startuml fig-sdn-traffic-policy
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title SDN Traffic Policy: Selective Permit and Drop by Protocol

participant "h1\n10.0.10.1" as H1 #FFE0B2
participant "s1 (OVS)\n+ Os-Ken" as S1 #90CAF9
participant "h2\n10.0.10.2" as H2 #C8E6C9
participant "h3\n10.0.10.3" as H3 #FFCDD2

== TCP between h1 and h2 — PERMITTED ==

H1 -[#43A047]> S1 : TCP SYN → h2 (packet_in)
S1 -[#43A047]> H2 : flow installed (priority 10)\nforward to port 2
H2 -[#43A047]> S1 : TCP SYN-ACK
S1 -[#43A047]> H1 : forward to port 1

== TCP towards h3 — BLOCKED ==

H1 -[#E53935]> S1 : TCP SYN → h3 (packet_in)
S1 -[#E53935]>x H3 : drop flow installed (priority 20)\nactions = [] (no output)

== UDP towards h3 — PERMITTED (after modification) ==

H1 -[#1565C0]> S1 : UDP → h3 (packet_in)
S1 -[#1565C0]> H3 : flow installed (ip_proto=17)\nforward to port 3
H3 -[#1565C0]> S1 : UDP reply
S1 -[#1565C0]> H1 : forward to port 1

legend right
  The controller inspects ip_proto:
  TCP (6) towards h3 → drop flow
  UDP (17) towards h3 → permit flow
  TCP between h1 ↔ h2 → permit flow
  This demonstrates fine-grained
  application-aware SDN policies.
endlegend
@enduml
